entry.title: Remove gfx::HDRMetadata from cc::TargetColorParams
entry.content:
This is towards taking cc::TargetColorParams out of the

cc::GpuImageDecodeCache key.



The gfx::HDRMetadata is extra information about an image, analogous to

the ICC profile. It does not belong in cc::TargetColorParams, which is

information about the color space that content is to be rasterized

into.



Remove gfx::HDRMetadata from cc::TargetColorParams, and place it on

cc::PaintImage.



At present, cc::PaintImage can also get the HDR metadata from its

cc::ImageHeaderMetadata. It may be preferable to move this at some

point.



Bug: 1483235

entry.title: DOM: Introduce the `Observer` dictionary for Observable
entry.content:
This CL introduces the `Observer` dictionary, which houses the

Observable subscription's `next()`, `complete()`, and `error()` handlers

as well as the optional `AbortSignal`. As of right now, these are all

unused, but a subsequent CL (https://crrev.com/c/4915345) will introduce

the `Subscriber` Web IDL interface, and implement its `next()`,

`complete()`, and `error()` methods to make them call the `Observer`

handlers appropriately. That subsequent CL will also implement the

appropriate error handling logic which ensures an Observer's `error()`

handler is called when it exists, and "report the exception" [1]

otherwise.



See

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NEobxgiQO-fTSocxJBqcOOOVZRmXcTFg9Iqrhebb7bg/edit.



[1]: https://html.spec.whatwg.org/C#report-the-exception

entry.title: Fix UaF in WebContentsFrameTracker
entry.content:
This patch fixes a use-after-free by moving to a base::WeakPtr

instead of a raw_ptr. Looking at the callstack in the referenced bug, what is clearly happening is that the frame tracker is deleted AFTER the capture device. I believe that this is due to the MouseCursorOverlayController being deleted through the DeleteOnUIThread destructor, which, if you are already on the UI thread, is synchronous:



https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/public/browser/browser_thread.h;l=141?q=BrowserThread::DeleteOnThread&ss=chromium%2Fchromium%2Fsrc



In comparison, the WebContentsFrameTracker is implemented using base::SequenceBound, which ends up calling an internal destruct method that ALWAYS posts back a task:



https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:base/threading/sequence_bound_internal.h;drc=f5bdc89c7395ed24f1b8d196a3bdd6232d5bf771;l=122



So, this bug is ultimately caused by the simple fact that base::SequenceBound does NOT have an optimization to not post a deletion task if we are already running on that sequence. There may be a good followup task here to change either DeleteOnThread or base::SequenceBound to have the same behavior, however I think this change a good first step.

entry.title: [GridNG] Report used values for `grid-template` ComputedStyle
entry.content:
Prior to this change, `grid-template` was using a shared method with

other grid shorthands for computed style values. This change splits

this into its own method for specific behavior.



The behavior implemented here is in response to this block from

the spec:



"Note: In general, resolved values are the computed values, except for

a small list of legacy 2.1 properties. However, compatibility with early

implementations of this module requires us to define grid-template-rows

and grid-template-columns as returning used values."

https://www.w3.org/TR/css-grid-2/#resolved-track-list-standalone



This specifically calls out `grid-template-rows` and

`grid-template-columns` as returning used values, which we were

previously *also* doing for `grid-template` via the shared method.

Since `grid-template` isn't listed here, we shouldn't actually be

doing this, and should be returning computed values as the test is

verifying. Firefox has already implemented this behavior.



The actual change here is pretty straightforward. The basic algorithm

is shared with `StylePropertySerializer::GetShorthandValueForGrid`,

and computed values are queried from `ValueForGridTrackList`, which

I did some slight renames to differentiate between computed and

used values. All of the shared logic is in CSSOMUtils.



After this, I'll push a small update to the last failing test, which

is slightly invalid. It should be placing the grid areas in the row

side, not on columns, as that is invalid and will never round-trip.

entry.title: Fix memory leak in RenderWidgetHostImpl unittest
entry.content:
The input tests allocate RenderWidgetHostImpls, but do not deallocate

them when the test ends. This memory leak is then flagged as dangling

entry.title: sensors: Make Blink Mojo requests go through a new WebSensorProvider interface
entry.content:
This is being done in preparation for adding the concept of "virtual

sensors" that implement the Automation section of the Generic Sensor

spec.



Virtual sensors manipulation is a privileged operation that should not

be exposed to Blink, so we now add a blink.mojom.WebSensorProvider

interface that it is supposed to use instead of

device.mojom.SensorProvider. FrameSensorProviderProxy in //content is

responsible for receiving WebSensorProvider requests and translating

them into SensorProvider ones that reach //services via

WebContentsSensorProviderProxy.



At the moment, both Mojo interfaces expose the same GetSensor() method,

but the idea is for SensorProvider to have extra virtual sensor methods

that WebSensorProvider will not.

This change:

`UNSUPPORTED_SCHEMES_TO_SPLIT` -> `SCHEMES_TO_SPLIT`

has been altered to not include scheme. Issues resolved:

- "localhost:1234" no longer produces scheme "localhost"

entry.title: Fix test bug in RegistryOverrideManager when using MOCK_TIME.
entry.content:
This CL fixed test bug in RegistryOverrideManager by using

base::subtle::TimeNowIgnoringOverride() instead of base::Time::Now() to

resolve RegistryOverrideManager test failure when using MOCK_TIME.



Background:

In base/test/test_reg_util_win.h, RegistryOverrideManager redirects part

of the registry to a temporary key. The temporary key contains a time

stamp, which "is used to delete stale keys left over from crashed

tests." This causes problems when MOCK_TIME is enabled, because

base::Time::Now() returns a timestamp from 1970.



When multiple tests run at the same time using RegistryOverrideManager,

new instances of RegistryOverrideManager will clean up any redirected

registry paths that have the timestamp from 1970, which then cause the

currently running tests to fail since their expected reg keys were

deleted by the other test.



Solution:

Use base::subtle::TimeNowIgnoringOverride() instead of base::Time::Now()

can give us the real current time instead of the mock time in 1970.

This can resolve related RegistryOverrideManager test failure when

using MOCK_TIME.



Test:

Corresponding test are added to verify the behavior, explanations listed

below:



We first create RegKey with mock time (1970), also create another RegKey

with GenerateTempKeyPath() - which is based on real time using

base::subtle::TimeNowIgnoringOverride().

Then we create RegistryOverrideManager with current time using

base::subtle::TimeNowIgnoringOverride(), after this, the key created

with mock time (1970) should be deleted, while the key created with

base::subtle::TimeNowIgnoringOverride() should still present.

Key created with mock time (1970) gets deleted represent the current bug

we found, the key created by calling GenerateTempKeyPath() represent

the new approach we are going for, and its presence after a new

RegistryOverrideManager being created validated that this key will not

get invalidated due to past time (1970) issue. Thus validated that this

test bug is resolved.







Bug: 1488676

entry.content:

DownloadItem, which can be dangling. This leads to a crash in dev

builds since the download is destroyed before the delegate, so a fix

to prevent this and future bugs if the logic in

ContentAnalysisDownloadsDelegate becomes more intricate is to make

it observe the download and update its pointer when that download is

destroyed.

entry.title: Moved last_recording_ to CanvasResourceProvider
entry.content:
The logic for preserving the last recording needed for vector

printing was distributed between the Canvas2DLayerBridge and the

CanvasResourceProvider, making the logic needlessly complex.

CanvasResourceProvider::FlushCanvas had logic for determining whether

the recording should be kept, but the Canvas2DLayerBridge was the one

keeping it. CanvasResourceProvider::FlushCanvas only returned the

recording if it meant for the bridge to keep it. This prevented any

other callers, unit tests for instance, from having access to flushed

recordings.



By moving all the logic to the provider, the code is simpler and

FlushCanvas can now return the recording unconditionally.



Bug: 1484741

entry.title: [web-tests] Fix incorrect fuzziness parameter minimums
entry.content:
A W(P)T may specify fuzziness parameters as either an inclusive range

[min, max], or a single expected value [1] (e.g., `totalPixels=30` means

exactly 30 pixels must be different for a test/reference to match).



This patch corrects a few tests that mistakenly reject exact matches

(i.e., maxDifference = totalPixels = 0) because they specify exact

nonzero parameters. WPT unfortunately doesn't interpret this as `0-`,

even though this is almost always what we want in practice.



`run_web_tests.py` allowed these parameters to land because it ignores

fuzzy parameters when the image hashes match exactly. Now, to be

consistent with [1] and its implementation in wptrunner, only skip

diffing when exact matches are expected.



[1]: https://web-platform-tests.org/writing-tests/reftests.html#fuzzy-matching



Bug: 1254776
